Transformation policy:
- Use one primary mechanism only.
- Work only the first unsatisfied tier, Tier T0 IPC/memory-core bound, until it is within tolerance.
- Add one compact frontend or control-flow perturbation in the existing hot path, such as a small unpredictable branch site or modest hot-footprint expansion, instead of jumping first to a backend stall mechanism.
- The new benchmark must materially change the timed hot path. Do not submit a rename-only clone, registration-only alias, or a bare noinline wrapper around identical work.
- Preserve the current benchmark's throughput-carrying structure.
- Do not change loop trip counts, benchmark scale, or the main steady-state serialization/deserialization or operation volume unless the controller objective explicitly requires it.
- IPC-CACHE COUPLING: The seed benchmark is compute-bound with much higher effective IPC than the target. Adding memory stalls (pointer-chasing through permuted arrays exceeding L1D capacity, data-dependent branches gated on load values) will SIMULTANEOUSLY lower IPC toward the target AND raise cache-miss and branch-miss counters. This coupling is expected — do not avoid memory-bound or branch-unpredictable patterns out of concern for IPC. Ensure the inner loop executes 100K+ iterations to dominate instruction count.
- MANDATORY CODE PATTERN — you MUST use this exact pointer-chasing + branch pattern inside the timed hot path. Simple if/else branches or linear array walks are NOT sufficient because hardware prefetchers and branch predictors learn them instantly:
```
// Setup: build linked-list pointer-chase chains
struct ChainNode { ChainNode* next; char pad[48]; }; // 64 bytes per node
// Hot chain: 1 MB (16384 nodes) — exceeds L1d (48KB), fits L2 (2MB)
static constexpr size_t kHotLen = 16384;
static ChainNode hotNodes[kHotLen];
// Cold chain: 128 MB (2M nodes) — exceeds LLC for DRAM misses
static constexpr size_t kColdLen = 2u << 20; // 2097152
static ChainNode* coldNodes = new ChainNode[kColdLen];
// Fisher-Yates shuffle to create Hamiltonian cycles
static void initChain(ChainNode* nodes, size_t len) {
  std::vector<size_t> perm(len);
  std::iota(perm.begin(), perm.end(), 0u);
  std::mt19937_64 rng(42);
  for (size_t i = len - 1; i > 0; --i)
    std::swap(perm[i], perm[rng() %% (i + 1)]);
  for (size_t i = 0; i < len; ++i)
    nodes[perm[i]].next = &nodes[perm[(i + 1) %% len]];
}
// 3 noinline 256-case switch functions (N ALU ops per case)
// — generates L1i pressure + branch misses via indirect misprediction
__attribute__((noinline)) uint64_t switchA(uint64_t v, int c) {
  switch(c) { case 0: v+=0x1234; v^=0x5678; /* ... 256 cases */ }
  return v;
}
// Inside timed loop:
ChainNode* hotPos = &hotNodes[0];
ChainNode* coldPos = &coldNodes[0];
uint64_t acc = 0;
for (size_t j = 0; j < INNER_ITERS; ++j) {
  hotPos = hotPos->next; // L1d miss (pointer-chase)
  uint64_t payload = (uint64_t)(uintptr_t)hotPos;
  // Rotate among 3 switch functions — L1i + branch misses
  switch (j %% 3) {
    case 0: acc = switchA(acc, payload & 0xFF); break;
    case 1: acc = switchB(acc, payload & 0xFF); break;
    case 2: acc = switchC(acc, payload & 0xFF); break;
  }
  // Branchless cold-chain access every N steps (LLC misses)
  auto coldMask = -uint64_t(j %% 8 == 0);
  coldPos = (ChainNode*)((uintptr_t)coldPos->next & coldMask
            | (uintptr_t)coldPos & ~coldMask);
}
folly::doNotOptimizeAway(acc);
```
Adapt this into the benchmark body. CRITICAL SIZING:
  - Hot chain: 1 MB (16384 x 64B) for L1d MPKI. Add 2-3 independent walkers for more L1d pressure.
  - Cold chain: 128 MB (2M x 64B) for LLC MPKI. Access frequency N controls LLC miss rate.
  - 3 switch functions x 256 cases x N ALU ops/case for L1i MPKI. Ops/case controls L1i linearly.
  - Iteration count MUST be >= 500K to dominate the instruction mix over framework overhead.
  - Use branchless cold-access scheduling to avoid TAGE predictor pollution.
